Henriette Avram, whose work here

00:02:41.480 --> 00:02:44.150
at LC replaced ink
on paper cataloging

00:02:44.150 --> 00:02:49.310
with distributed electronic
cataloging records.

00:02:49.310 --> 00:02:55.100
Henriette Avram was born in New
York in 1919, she did two years

00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:57.780
of pre-med at Hunter College
and then left to start a family.

00:02:57.780 --> 00:03:01.240
She was in her 30s when she
started learning how to program.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:03.810
And I really like this story
because there are people

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:06.330
who will still tell you that if you
haven't been coding since you were

00:03:06.330 --> 00:03:08.710
in diapers, you'll
never be able to do it.

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:11.180
And I'm here to tell
you that they're wrong.

00:03:11.180 --> 00:03:13.490
She did it and she
changed the world.

00:03:17.830 --> 00:03:21.540
Henriette and her team here
at the library created MARC,

00:03:21.540 --> 00:03:24.290
which is a structure to hold
bibliographic information

00:03:24.290 --> 00:03:26.260
for materials of all formats.

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:30.070
Does anybody in the room
remember card catalogs?

00:03:30.070 --> 00:03:32.330
There are people like
that Colleen's age

00:03:32.330 --> 00:03:35.190
that do not remember it
so don't laugh at me.

00:03:35.190 --> 00:03:39.580
I really do miss the beauty
of them and the smell.

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:41.670
Like do you remember
how they used to smell?

00:03:41.670 --> 00:03:43.380
But that's about all I miss.

00:03:43.380 --> 00:03:45.630
They were kind of hard
to use, right?

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:51.450
And what Henriette and her team
gave us is the power to share

00:03:51.450 --> 00:03:54.750
that information across oceans
and search it at a keystroke.

00:03:54.750 --> 00:03:57.010
So right now I can sit at my
desk and search the holdings

00:03:57.010 --> 00:03:58.690
of the British Library
to decide whether I want

00:03:58.690 --> 00:04:00.260
to take a plane flight over there.

00:04:00.260 --> 00:04:03.000
In the past, that would
have been impossible.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.200
It also gave us the ability to
do really good precision recall,

00:04:06.200 --> 00:04:08.540
you know, like searching with
a search string is much easier

00:04:08.540 --> 00:04:10.390
than looking up beagle
and then realizing,

00:04:10.390 --> 00:04:13.050
well that's not how someone
intended to catalog it,

00:04:13.050 --> 00:04:16.100
you have to look up
a different name.

00:04:16.100 --> 00:04:18.170
It, it also gave us shareability.

00:04:18.170 --> 00:04:20.740
So it's the kind of work that
I find really interesting.

00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:24.520
An application of effort here
made everybody's life a little

00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:25.820
bit better.

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:28.400
So we could swap cataloging
records, we could have joint teams

00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:32.550
where we could do the
copy cataloging.

00:04:32.550 --> 00:04:35.100
You know, it really
improved all of our lives.

00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:41.380
I think of Henriette Avram as sort

00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:43.290
of a hidden hero of
computer science.

00:04:43.290 --> 00:04:45.380
She's a personal hero of mine.

00:04:45.380 --> 00:04:49.190
She came to libraries
from software like I did,

00:04:49.190 --> 00:04:54.120
and really took her adopted home
as a place of her heart like I do.

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:57.590
But she did all of this before
computers were networked,

00:04:57.590 --> 00:05:00.090
before relational databases
were a thing,

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:02.450
before character encoding
was really mature.

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:05.460
And I really like to just take
a moment and reflect on like,

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:08.910
what she was able to give
us at a time that you know,

00:05:08.910 --> 00:05:12.100
this kind of sharing of information
was really, very limited.

00:05:12.100 --> 00:05:16.060
And I think also when I think about
her story, it shows me the power

00:05:16.060 --> 00:05:19.010
of combining disciplines,
which she did in her own self,

00:05:19.010 --> 00:05:22.210
and I think that, knowing
many of you, that you do, too.

00:05:22.210 --> 00:05:25.840
Right? You know, you have a data
science background and you work

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:29.660
in libraries, or you're a software
developer who's also a journalist.

00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:30.960
And she did that herself.

00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:33.180
But also we do that by
having rooms like this

00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:35.980
where we share our knowledge
and get to know each other.

00:05:35.980 --> 00:05:40.140
And I think that that's where
we see really cool seat changes,

00:05:40.140 --> 00:05:43.910
where we can provide,
like cross disciplines.

00:05:43.910 --> 00:05:49.520
Her work really started the digital
revolution in information science

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:53.120
and it's something we
carry forward today.

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:56.540
Here at the Library of Congress
but also broadly in the field.

00:05:56.540 --> 00:05:58.580
I think about her as the person

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:02.610
who really started libraries'
commitment to open source.

00:06:02.610 --> 00:06:05.190
So for those of you who work
in software in the libraries,

00:06:05.190 --> 00:06:09.540 position:56%
we're avid users and contributors to
open source but also standards work.

00:06:09.540 --> 00:06:11.850
You know, we're famous for
getting committees together

00:06:11.850 --> 00:06:13.610
and all working together, right?

00:06:13.610 --> 00:06:17.930
And I think it really does lift the
tide, and that's the kind of work

00:06:17.930 --> 00:06:19.510
that I'm really excited about.

00:06:19.510 --> 00:06:24.140
It also shows, to me, how
innovation can look like a dot

00:06:24.140 --> 00:06:26.310
in the timeline, but
it's really not.

00:06:26.310 --> 00:06:30.980
So people say things like MARC was
released to the public in 1968.

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:35.310
But really it was ten years
of iterative releases,

00:06:35.310 --> 00:06:39.410
and it only looks like a dot
in a timeline in hindsight.

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:41.870
And you can, and it still
continues to improve today.

00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:43.410
You know, we have teams
of people working

00:06:43.410 --> 00:06:45.800
on the standard here
and internationally.

00:06:45.800 --> 00:06:49.520
It's an international standard
that now contains character support

00:06:49.520 --> 00:06:51.090
for all current used languages.

00:06:51.090 --> 00:06:55.930
You know? So it's this thing
that continues to blossom.

00:06:55.930 --> 00:07:01.130
And I think about that in
relation to other work here

00:07:01.130 --> 00:07:04.100
at the library, like LOC.gov.

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:06.350
It's also another dot
in the timeline

00:07:06.350 --> 00:07:08.210 position:56%
but is also a continuous improvement

00:07:08.210 --> 00:07:10.150
and we add new collections
all the time.

00:07:10.150 --> 00:07:13.210
My colleagues and OCIO
and library services,

00:07:13.210 --> 00:07:14.680
put forward an enormous
amount of work

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:17.740
to release these new
treasures to the public.

00:07:17.740 --> 00:07:20.040
Just this year we released a lot

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:23.150
of new collections including
George Patton's diaries,

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:26.180
the Chicago Ethnic Arts Projects,
and Walt Whitman's papers.

00:07:26.180 --> 00:07:30.970
And I want to zoom down one more
level and just take a close look

00:07:30.970 --> 00:07:32.990
at one collection that
we've released.

00:07:32.990 --> 00:07:35.190
And we could just as easily
be looking at another,

00:07:35.190 --> 00:07:36.980
at any of the other collections

00:07:36.980 --> 00:07:39.180
like the ballroom dancing
instruction manuals

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:41.460
which are a hoot, you should
really check them out.

00:07:41.460 --> 00:07:44.760
Or the 2014 election web archives.

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:47.810
But I picked this one because it's
really special to me and I find it,

00:07:47.810 --> 00:07:51.380
I think it's really exciting.

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:55.030
Rosa Parks' personal papers and on
loan to the library for ten years

00:07:55.030 --> 00:07:57.130 position:56%
from the Howard G Buffet foundation.

00:07:57.130 --> 00:08:00.500
They contain 7,500 pieces of
personal correspondence and papers

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:05.860
and 2,500 Princeton photographs
documenting her private life

00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:10.110
and public activism on behalf of
civil rights for African Americans.

00:08:10.110 --> 00:08:13.380
The materials came here, they
were assessed and stabilized

00:08:13.380 --> 00:08:15.320
by the LC conservation division.

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:18.000
They were cataloged and described
by librarians and archivists.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.010
Files were moved by
people and software.

00:08:21.010 --> 00:08:23.760
They were assessed,
validated, prepared for access.

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:25.380
Meta-data was transformed.

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:26.870
Websites were created.

00:08:26.870 --> 00:08:29.640
Search index were populated
and rights were assessed.

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:34.010
That's a few years worth of work
in less than 140 characters.

00:08:34.010 --> 00:08:39.590
And those of you that are
librarians in the room,

00:08:39.590 --> 00:08:41.380
you know that this is
just the job, right?

00:08:41.380 --> 00:08:45.230
A bunch of invisible work to make
information find-able and usable.

00:08:45.230 --> 00:08:47.590
But I kind of want to
make a big deal out of it

00:08:47.590 --> 00:08:51.210
because we make a big
splash for cool new websites

00:08:51.210 --> 00:08:55.280
and exciting new visualizations
but the sustained and careful

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:56.850 position:56%
that it takes to get new information

00:08:56.850 --> 00:08:59.760
out is something I think
we should really celebrate.

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:02.110
And I think it also
speaks to something

00:09:02.110 --> 00:09:05.080
that I've been thinking a lot
about, which is this tension

00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:06.970
between innovation
and sustainability.

00:09:06.970 --> 00:09:10.910
And I think about this
in terms of LOC.gov

00:09:10.910 --> 00:09:14.470
and the sustained effort takes
in getting new collections ready,

00:09:14.470 --> 00:09:18.480
and the enduring power of MARC
and other bibliographic standards

00:09:18.480 --> 00:09:23.980
like big frame, and I think of
Henriette Avram as my shiny beacon.

00:09:23.980 --> 00:09:26.910
Because her, you know, level
of software in libraries,

00:09:26.910 --> 00:09:30.110 position:56%
but also because she really believed
in the power of infrastructure.

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:32.410
Which is something that I
can get really excited about,

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:34.390
like I think infrastructure's
really cool.

00:09:34.390 --> 00:09:37.430 position:56%
You know? It's the roads that we
all drive to get cool places, right?

00:09:37.430 --> 00:09:41.540
And I think that groups like ours,
like National Digital Initiatives,

00:09:41.540 --> 00:09:45.380
can either become or be perceived
as like, the cool new things group.

00:09:45.380 --> 00:09:47.120
And I really don't want to do that.

00:09:47.120 --> 00:09:51.750
I want to do things that lift the
tide and have a view to the future.

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:54.290
So with that all in mind as
we were doing our planning

00:09:54.290 --> 00:09:56.770
for National Digital Initiatives,
we came up with a couple of goals

00:09:56.770 --> 00:10:00.040
that I'd like to share
with you today.

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:03.220
The first one is to maximize
the digital collection,

00:10:03.220 --> 00:10:04.600
the benefit of the
digital collection

00:10:04.600 --> 00:10:06.640
to the American public
and to the world.

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:10.460
We have a lot of stuff here
at LC, we have a lot of it,

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:12.370
and a lot of it's publicly
available in digital.

00:10:12.370 --> 00:10:15.810
We have 10 million historic
digital newspaper pages,

00:10:15.810 --> 00:10:19.350
we have 1.2 million
prints and photographs,

00:10:19.350 --> 00:10:23.190
we have the personal papers of
George Washington, Lincoln, Carlsig

00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:25.770
and Jackie Robinson
and many other maps,

00:10:25.770 --> 00:10:28.410
books and archived websites
and other treasures.

00:10:28.410 --> 00:10:31.450
We have this really awesome team
here called educational outreach,

00:10:31.450 --> 00:10:34.670
I don't know how many of you have
heard of it, but they focus on K

00:10:34.670 --> 00:10:37.860
through 12 educators and students
and they prepare resources

00:10:37.860 --> 00:10:42.960
and programs that help teachers
get material out to their students

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:45.600
from the library, teaching
with primary sources.

00:10:45.600 --> 00:10:48.240
And I'd like to think about
how we can extend the benefit

00:10:48.240 --> 00:10:52.110
that they give to advanced
scholars and to the public

00:10:52.110 --> 00:10:55.210
and to the curious, and how
do we teach a new generation

00:10:55.210 --> 00:10:57.080
of journalists to come to
the Library of Congress

00:10:57.080 --> 00:10:59.730
for reference help
and for resources?

00:10:59.730 --> 00:11:01.030
I think that's the kind of thing

00:11:01.030 --> 00:11:03.660
that would be really
exciting to work on.

00:11:03.660 --> 00:11:07.940
We'd also like to enable more
creative reuse of the collection.

00:11:07.940 --> 00:11:11.790
The great mustaches of LOC, I tried
to grow one today for an example,

00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:13.540
but it didn't really work out.

00:11:13.540 --> 00:11:18.860
And people use these like for mugs
and t-shirts, and it's really neat

00:11:18.860 --> 00:11:21.900
to see that kind of economic
benefit from things that are

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:26.080
in the public collective, but it
also, in its fun and exciting,

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:29.680
and it brings people to the
collection, too, which is great,

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:33.610
but it also services a more
important scholarly purpose, too.

00:11:33.610 --> 00:11:36.500
Back to the Rosa Parks
collection for a second,

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:40.220
